looking to replace pet blue jay was the best pet ive ever had where can i find another one houston tx i cant tell you how awsome of a friend elvin my blue jay was would give anything to find another baby blue jay possession of a bluejay unless you have the proper permits is against federal law all native migratory birds are protected by the migratory bird treaty act http www npwrc usgs gov about faqs birds feathers htm states anyone desiring to possess migratory birds or their parts or products should be aware that all of these are covered under the migratory bird treaty act u s c which implements a series of international treaties designed to protect migratory birds some key provisions of the act are worth keeping in mind wording of the act makes it very clear that most actions that result in taking or possession of a protected species or its parts or products is a violation of the act specifically the act states unless and except as permitted by regulations it shall be unlawful at any time by any means or in any manner to pursue hunt take capture kill possess offer for sale sell purchase import any migratory bird any part nest or eggs of any such bird it is a strict liability law meaning that there is no requirement for law enforcement agencies to prove intent to violate the law that is if you are found in possession of a protected species or its parts or products you are automatically in violation of the law the provisions of the act are nearly absolute except as permitted by regulations is the only exception some examples of permitted activities that do not violate the law are legal hunting of specific game birds legitimate research activities display in licensed zoological gardens and bird banding under an appropriate permit the act covers the great majority of all native birds found in the u s many of the species not covered by the act are covered by the endangered species act other federal laws or state laws many of which are as stringent as the migratory bird treaty act in the lower states all species except the house sparrow feral pigeon common starling and non migratory game birds like pheasants gray partridge and sage grouse are protected penalties upon conviction can be severe even if a sympathetic jury finds that you meant no harm in trying to rear an abandoned nestling or in picking a hawk feather legal defense costs are clearly not worth the risk Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Hunting Treaty Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918 Freedom of speech Trademark Controlled Substances Act Introduced species Appeal Contract Intellectual property Plame affair First Amendment to the United States Constitution Due process Constitution of Ireland Child pornography United States Constitution Fair use Slander and libel Cannabis rescheduling in the United States Gun politics Law Falconry Public domain Copyright Cat House Sparrow Online Copyright Infringement Liability Limitation Act Environmental Protection Agency Digital rights management Endangered Species Act Article One of the United States Constitution Microeconomics Gun politics in the United States Conspiracy Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe Kashrut Estoppel Equal Protection Clause Australian constitutional law USA PATRIOT Act Tax Classified information Country parks and conservation in Hong Kong Insurance Corporation Copyright law of the United Kingdom Article Three of the United States Constitution Arguments for and against drug prohibition Copyleft Same-sex marriage in the United States Supreme Court of the United States Juris Doctor Convention on Psychotropic Substances Constitution Food and Drug Administration Spyware Consensual crime International law Peregrine Falcon Peafowl Fox hunting Free trade International conventions on terrorism Kakapo Whistleblower Prohibition Constitution of Australia Fauna of Australia Password Capitalism Patent Animal rights Civil rights Separation of church and stat